Analysis of US loan data (2005-2014) by Christopher Buss

Univariate Plots Section

There are two main reasons for me to use the prosper loan data. First, because it is a highly relevant societal topic as we have seen how the dept crisis in the US in 2008 lead to a global recession. Second, because I have recently bougt a flat and I am interested which factors determine interest rates for individual customers. I begin the exploration with an univariate analysis of the dataset.

Loans

The number of loans fluctuates over time. There is a steep increase towards the end of the period of investigation.

BorrowerRate

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0000  0.1340  0.1840  0.1928  0.2500  0.4975

## [1] "Modus:"
## [1] "0.3177"

The mean interest rate for all loans is about 19%. The distribution approximates a normal distribution with a high peak at exactly 31.77%. This might be a problem with the data or could be a result of a special offer for loans at this rate.

Overall, the median rate is surprisingly stable over time. However, there is an increase in the second half of 2010 and a decrease on the previous level from 2012 onwards.

Amount

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    1000    4000    6500    8337   12000   35000

The amount of the loans ranges from $1,000 to $35,000 with a median loan of $6,500. There are several suspisious peaks in the distribution.

Zooming in, I see that these peaks represent multiplikates of $500 and $1000. There are peaks in the distribution at $4,000, $10,000, $15,000, $20,000 and $25,000. Because of the skewed distribution I decide to use a log scale for this variable, leading to a distribution that is closer to a normal distribution.

Monthly income

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##       0    3200    4667    5608    6825 1750003

The Boxplot reveals that there is one extreme outlier with $1,750,003 monthly income, a yearly income of moren than $21 Million. It is not impossible, but highly unlikely that someone with such a high income needs a loan of a few thousand Dollars. Therefore, I assume an error in the data and exclude this case from
further analyses.

Because of the skewed distribution, I decide to use a log scale for the income variable.

# Excluding cases with unrealistic income
df <- subset(df, Income < 1750000)

# Transform income to log-scale
df$IncomeLog <- log(df$Income+1)
ggplot(aes(x = IncomeLog), data = df) +
  geom_histogram(breaks=seq(6,11, by=0.1))

I calculate the share of the monthly payments from the total loan. The majority of payments are about 20%-40% of the total loan. There are some extreme outliers with payments much higher than the total loan. I exclude these cases from the analysis because these do not seem to be valid values to me.

Employment status

## 
##                    Employed     Full-time Not available  Not employed 
##          2200         67045         25804          5238           824 
##         Other     Part-time       Retired Self-employed 
##          3797          1045           775          6087

The categories of the employment status variable are not mutually exclusive and the missings are coded in different ways. Therefore, I recode the variable. Because I do not want to exclude all missings on this variable in a later regression, I do not mark these cases as “NA” but as “unknown”.

# Recode employment
df$Employment_re<-car::recode(df$EmploymentStatus,
    "c('Employed', 'Full-time') = 'Employed';
    c('Other', 'Not available', '') = 'Unknown' ")

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 113,937 observations and 82 variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest is the borrower rate. I suspect that certain aspects of the borrower and the loan itself are related to the borrower rate.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation?

In particular, I assume the following features are useful for my predictive model: *Aspects of the borrower** * Prosper scores * Income * Dept to income ratio

*Aspects of the loan** * Amount * Monthly payment relative to loan * Term of the loan

I also assume that other factors such as the recommendations might be related to the interest rate. However, these variables contain little variance and therefore are left out of the further analysis. Occupation could also be interesting, but I would need to combine the many categories in a sensible way, which goes beyond the scope of this EDA.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I calculate the share of the monthly payments from the total loan. I recoded the variable for employment status by combining categories. Also, I recoded term from a continous to a categorial variable.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Income and the total amount of the loan exhibited skewed distributions. Therefore, I calculated the logs for these values.

Bivariate Plots Section

These plots show the correlations between the variables of interest. I proceed with a closer look at variables that show a strong relationship or unusual patterns.

Scatterplots - Borrower rate and independent variables

ProsperScore is clearly related to BorrowerRate. Individuals with the worst score pay amout three times more interest rates than individuals with the best score. There is an interesting break in the line between scores 5 and 6, showing that there is no difference in the Borrower rate between these groups.

There is a very interesting pattern for the second plot. There is a negative relationship between the monthly loan payment (as share of the loan) and borrower rate. However, there are different trajectories in the data. This needs more exploration in the multivariate part.

Scatterplots - independent variables

There are also interesting patterns in regard to the independent variables.

Loan status over time

The status of the loans is related to the quarter in which the loan originated. From the earlier quarters, all loans are either completed, defaulted on or cancelled. This reflects the short loan period in the data set. There is a surprisingly high share of loans that defaulted, in particular in the years 2007 and 2008. This is possibly related to the economic crisis in these years.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part

Overall, the choosen variables in the data set are highly correlated. Most interesting for the aim of this project are the correlations between BorrowerRate and the other variables. There is a negative relationship between BorrowerRate and monthly payment (both in absolute terms and as share of the loan), the amount of the loan, and prosper score.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features  (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

The independent variables are also correlated with each other. For example, there is a positive relationship between personal income on the one hand, and the amount, monthly payment and prosper score on the other hand. Individuals with a high income recieve bigger loans with better conditions than individuals with little income.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is between BorrowerRate and ProsperScore.

Multivariate Plots Section

The interesting relationship between BorrowerRate and LoanPaymentPerc seem to be related to either the status of the loan or the quarter. Those data points on the “lines” in the plot are predominantly loans that are recent (2011 onwards) and current. Older, completed loans often diverge from this pattern.

Apparently, ProsperScores are also related to the other two variables of interest. For all individuals with a score assigned, the monthly payment describes perfectly the interest rate. For individuals without a score (=earlier loans), there is much more dispersion.

Another interesting pattern emerges when plotting the distribution of BorrowerRate across the legth of the loan. Borrower rates increase with term length, but the rates of medium-length loans are more dispersed.

In the last step I conduct a multivariate regression analysis with BorrowerRate as dependent variable. I include independent variables stepwise in the model. ProsperScore expains about 42% of the DV’s variance. With each more Scoring-Point, BorrowerRate is about 0.2 percentage points lower. Judged by R², this is the most important predictor of interest rates in the data. From the other variables, the length of the loan (TermRe) is also quite important. About 30% additional explained variance can be attributed to this variable. Overall, with an R² of about 0.83 the model fits the data quite well.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part
Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

There is an interesting relationship between ProsperScore, LoanPaymentPerc and BorrowerRate. For the most recent loans, LoanPaymentPerc is a very good predictor for BorrowerRate. For older loans, the relationship us much weaker.

Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss limitations!

I calculated a linear regression model with the interest rate as dependent variable, and ProsperScore, AmountLog, IncomeLog, LoanPaymentPerc, TermRe and DebtToIncomeRatio as independent variables.

Some other variables in the dataset related to the credit history of the person could be of interest. Another limitation is that these results indicate correlation, but not causation.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This matrix shows the distributions and correlations of the most important variables in the analysis. The main variable of interest, the borrower’s interest rate (BorrowerRate), is related to several other variables in the dataset. The most important predictor seem to be the borrower’s score (ProsperScore).

Plot Two

Description Two

The relationship between BorrowerRate and ProsperScore is further illustrated with this plot. While there is still some variability in the data, there is a clear downward trend of the interest rate in case of better scores.

Plot Three

Description Three

The third plot visualizes the relationship between interest rate, monthly payment and score. For all individuals with a score assigned, the monthly payment describes perfectly the interest rate. For individuals without a score (=earlier loans), there is much more dispersion.

Reflection

Overall, the results are not surprising - the interest rate largely depends on the credibility of the borrower and the characteristics of the loan. I am still puzzled by Plot 3 in my summary. I cannot explain the pattern in this graph, but I assume that the interest rate is calculated differently for old (completed) loans than for newer (current) loans. However, this point needs further exploration.

I did struggle a bit with the R-syntax at times because I am a genuine user of STATA. In particular, I had to use some workarounds to make the plots over time work. However, the graph functions in R a really nice!

Future analysis of the dataset could explore the following points: * How can be predict if a borrower defaults on a loan? * Are there regional differences between states? * How can we predict someone’s ProsperScore?
